Transcriptomic analysis of adult uganda dataset

N Khambati

2023-04-30

Nasal cells analysis

This R Markdown document shows the exploratory analysis of the nasal cells dataset from Ugandan adults.
N = 26: controls = 15, cases = 11.
Differential gene expression was done using DESEQ2, with cases as the reference group.

Volcano plots

#### Make an advanced volcano plot which has a legend, grouped by colour ####

# To do so we need to make a new table of just the first 5 rows in master_sig_tables:
master_sig_up_top5 = master_sig_up[1:5,] #  nb: there is only 3 signif upreg genes 
master_sig_down_top5 = master_sig_down[1:5,]

ggplot(master, aes(x=log2fold, y=mlog10p.adj)) + 
  geom_point(aes(colour = "a")) + 
  geom_point(data = master_sig_up, aes(colour = "b")) +
  geom_point(data = master_sig_down, aes(colour = "c")) +
  labs(title = "Volcano Plot", x= "Log2 fold change", y= "-Log10 p") +
  theme_classic() +
  geom_vline(xintercept= -1, linetype="dashed", colour="grey", size=0.5) +
  geom_vline(xintercept= 1, linetype="dashed", colour="grey", size=0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=-log10(0.05), linetype="dashed", colour="grey", size=0.5) +
  geom_text_repel(data=master_sig_up_top5, aes(label=gene_name, colour= "b"), show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text_repel(data=master_sig_down_top5, aes(label=gene_name, colour= "c"), show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("black", "red", "blue"), labels=c("No change", "up","down"), name="") 
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_text_repel()`).

MA Plots

#### Make an advanced MA plot which has a legend, grouped by colour ####

ggplot(master, aes(x=log10(mean_counts), y=log2fold)) +
  #add points
  geom_point(aes(colour = "a")) + 
  geom_point(data = master_sig_up, aes(colour = "b")) +
  geom_point(data = master_sig_down, aes(colour = "c")) +

  geom_hline(yintercept=1,linetype="dashed") +
  # add axis labels and the title
  labs(title = "MA plot", x= "Mean Expression (log10)", y= "Log2 fold change") +
  # add data labels
  geom_text_repel(data=master_sig_up_top5, aes(label=gene_name), show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text_repel(data=master_sig_down_top5, aes(label=gene_name), show.legend = FALSE) +
  # set colours and labels as you want

  # add theme

Expression density plots

#### Make a expression density plot with facets, coloured by type of sample ####

em_groups <- em
# this loop says take the first sample and set all its expression values to be the name of the group
# then repeat for each sample
for (index in 1:ncol(em_groups))
{
  group = ss[index, "sample_group"]
  em_groups[,index] = group
}

#melt this new table
em_groups <- melt(em_groups, id.vars = NULL)
#now make the plot
em.m <- melt(em)
## No id variables; using all as measure variables
em.m$groups <- em_groups$value

ggplot(em.m, aes(x = log10(value+0.01), fill=groups)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.75) +
  facet_wrap(~variable, ncol=4) +
  labs(x = "Expression (log10)", y = "Density") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(strip.background = element_rect(fill="transparent", size = 0))

Heatmaps

#### Make a heatmap clustered by Y axis  ####

# Only look at significant genes
# You need to use scaled data
# Clustering neeeds a matrix, not a dataframe

# Heatmap clustered by y axis (the gene I think here)

# first choose your colours and make a palette 
# for other options see tutorial 10
colours <-  c("blue", "pink", "red")
palette <- colorRampPalette(colours)(100)

# Make a matrix and cluster the expression matrix by y axis

# make a matrix
hm.matrix <- as.matrix(em_scaled_sig)
# get the distances- i.e. works out the correlations
# do this BEFORE we melt but AFTER converting to matrix 
y.dist = Dist(hm.matrix, method="spearman")
# perform the clustering using the distance i.e. build the dendrogram
y.cluster = hclust(y.dist, method="average")
# extract the dendrogram #
y.dd = as.dendrogram(y.cluster)
# untangle the dendogram (re-order it)
y.dd.reorder = reorder(y.dd,0,FUN="average")

# extract the untangled gene order from the denrogram- 
# i.e. gets the new gene order as a vector of row indices and removes the dendogram part
y.order = order.dendrogram(y.dd.reorder)

# now this reorders the heatmap matrix in the new clustered gene order
hm.matrix_clustered = hm.matrix[y.order,]

# now melt
hm.matrix_clustered = melt(hm.matrix_clustered)
# Final plot (last line of code removes sample name: for e.g if they are squished)
ggplot(hm.matrix_clustered, aes(x=Var2, y=Var1, fill=value)) + 
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = palette) +
  ylab("gene") +
  xlab("sample") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks=element_blank(), legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.spacing.x = unit(0.25, 'cm'))

#### Make a heat map clustered by the X axis ####

# cluster by samples in this dataset

# make a matrix. 
hm.matrix <- as.matrix(em_scaled_sig)
# transpose- this is the key step
hm.matrix = t(hm.matrix)
# gets the distances- works out the correlations
y.dist = Dist(hm.matrix, method="spearman")
# perform the clustering using the distance i.e. build the dendrogram
y.cluster = hclust(y.dist, method="average")
# extract the dendrogram 
y.dd = as.dendrogram(y.cluster)
# untangle the dendogram (re-order it)
y.dd.reorder = reorder(y.dd,0,FUN="average")

# this gets the untangled gene order from the dendoogram- 
# i.e. gets the new sample order as a vector of row indices and removes the dendogram part
y.order = order.dendrogram(y.dd.reorder)
# now this reorders the original heatmap matrix in the new clustered sample order
hm.matrix_clustered = hm.matrix[y.order,]

# now melt and plot
hm.matrix_clustered = melt(hm.matrix_clustered)
ggplot(hm.matrix_clustered, aes(x=Var1, y=Var2, fill=value)) + 
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = palette) +
  ylab("gene") +
  xlab("sample") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks=element_blank(), legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.spacing.x = unit(0.25, 'cm'))

#### Make a heat map clustered by X & Y axis (genes and samples) ####

# make a matrix. 
hm.matrix = as.matrix(em_scaled_sig)

# gets the distances- works out the correlations
x.dist = Dist(t(hm.matrix), method = "spearman")
y.dist = Dist(hm.matrix, method = "spearman")

#Then we actually cluster via distance
x.cluster = hclust(x.dist, method="average")
y.cluster = hclust(y.dist, method="average")

#Extract the dendogram
x.dd = as.dendrogram(x.cluster)
y.dd = as.dendrogram(y.cluster)

#Untangle/reorder the dendogram
x.dd.reorder = reorder(x.dd, 0, FUN="average")
y.dd.reorder = reorder(y.dd, 0, FUN="average")

#Then we can get the new gene order as a vector of the row indexes
x.order = order.dendrogram(x.dd.reorder)
y.order = order.dendrogram(y.dd.reorder)

#Then we reorder the heatmap matrix to have the new, clustered gene order
hm.matrix_clustered = hm.matrix[y.order,x.order]

#Finally, we can melt the data & make our heatmap
hm.matrix_clustered = melt(hm.matrix_clustered)

ggplot(hm.matrix_clustered,aes(x=Var2, y=Var1, fill=value))+
  geom_tile()+
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = palette)+
  ggtitle("Heatmap of significantly expressed genes (x & y clustered)")+
  xlab("Sample")+
  ylab("") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks=element_blank(), legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.spacing.x = unit(0.25, 'cm'))
